SubTopics: Analyze and compare properties of metals, plastics, wood, and ceramics, including flexibility, ductility, hardness, thermal conductivity, electrical conductivity, and melting point.
Content: The arrow in the picture points to a part of the Golden Gate Bridge made of concrete.
problems/MA19G8S/media/1a.jpg
Which of the following best explains why the engineers used concrete to build this part of the bridge?

A.Choice: Concrete is low in density so this part of the bridge can float on top of the water.

B.Choice: Concrete is very heavy so this part of the bridge can move back and forth in the wind.

C.Choice: Concrete is low in density so this part of the bridge can move back and forth in the wind.

D.Choice: Concrete is high in strength so this part of the bridge can support a large amount of weight.

SubTopics: Develop a model that describes and predicts changes in particle motion, relative spatial arrangement, temperature, and state of a pure substance when thermal energy is added or removed.
Content: A student makes this particle model of atoms that make up part of the bridge. The model shows the atoms when the bridge is at 18°C.
problems/MA19G8S/media/2a.jpg
The student wants to make a new model to show the atoms when the bridge is heated to 23°C.
Which of the following changes should the student include in the new model?

B.Choice: making the atoms a different shape

C.Choice: making larger spaces between the atoms

D.Choice: making chemical bonds between the atoms

SubTopics: Use diagrams of a simple wave to explain that (a) a wave has a repeating pattern with a specific amplitude, frequency, and wavelength, and (b) the amplitude of a wave is related to the energy of the wave.
Content: Small earthquakes are relatively common near the Golden Gate Bridge, but major earthquakes occur less often. Major earthquakes only occur when a large amount of energy is carried by seismic waves.
Which of the following must be large for a major earthquake to occur?

A.Choice: the speed of the seismic waves

B.Choice: the frequency of the seismic waves

C.Choice: the amplitude of the seismic waves

D.Choice: the wavelength of the seismic waves

SubTopics: Show how the components of a structural system work together to serve a structural function. Provide examples of physical structures and relate their design to their intended use.
Content: :ibox:𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗤𝗨𝗘𝗦𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡 𝗛𝗔𝗦 𝗧𝗛𝗥𝗘𝗘 𝗣𝗔𝗥𝗧𝗦.

The students work in teams to create and test models of bridges made of straws and tape. The bridges are built between two tables, which are not considered part of the bridge. The diagram shows a bridge created by one of the teams.
problems/MA19G8S/media/4a.jpg
The team tests the strength of the bridge by adding coins, one at a time, to the deck of the bridge. The team records how many coins the bridge can support before it collapses.
Identify what the coins most likely represent in this test.
Identify 𝗔𝗟𝗟 the materials that are a part of the total load of the bridge when the team tests the strength of the bridge.
The team then adds more straws and tape and tests the strength of the bridge again.
Describe one advantage 𝗔𝗡𝗗 one disadvantage of adding more materials.

SubTopics: Use a model to illustrate that energy from Earth's interior drives convection that cycles Earth's crust, leading to melting, crystallization, weathering, and deformation of large rock formations, including generation of ocean sea floor at ridges, submergence of ocean sea floor at trenches, mountain building, and active volcanic chains.
Content: :ibox:𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗤𝗨𝗘𝗦𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡 𝗛𝗔𝗦 𝗧𝗛𝗥𝗘𝗘 𝗣𝗔𝗥𝗧𝗦.
The diagram shows two oceanic plates, plate W and plate X. The plates are moving toward each other, with plate X being pushed under plate W.
problems/MA19G8S/media/5a.jpg
Identify one geological feature that will form as plate X is pushed under plate W.
Describe what happens to the solid material of plate X when it is pushed beneath plate W. Explain why this happens.
Describe the process that causes the plates to move toward each other. In your answer, be sure to identify the layer of Earth where this process occurs.

SubTopics: Develop and use a model to show that sexually reproducing organisms have two of each chromosome in their cell nuclei, and hence two variants (alleles) of each gene that can be the same or different from each other, with one random assortment of each chromosome passed down to offspring from both parents.
Content: Two pea plants are crossed. Each parent plant has a dominant allele for height (H) and a recessive allele for height (h).
Which of the following shows the expected percentage of each genotype for the offspring of these parents?

SubTopics: Evaluate competing solutions to a given design problem using a decision matrix to determine how well each meets the criteria and constraints of the problem. Use a model of each solution to evaluate how variations in one or more design features, including size, shape, weight, or cost, may affect the function or effectiveness of the solution.
Content: A large puddle forms in a low area of a park every time it rains. Visitors to the park complain about the puddle. A landscaper is considering two design solutions to solve the problem:

:ibox:• Solution 1: adding dirt to build up the low area so rainwater becomes runoff instead of a puddle

• Solution 2: creating a rain garden so rainwater becomes groundwater instead of a puddle
The diagrams show an example of each solution.
problems/MA19G8S/media/7a.jpg
problems/MA19G8S/media/7b.jpg
Which of the following is the main advantage of solution 2 compared to solution 1?

A.Choice: The rain garden would take less time to make.

B.Choice: The rain garden would be less expensive to maintain.

C.Choice: The rain garden would help prevent erosion of the area.

D.Choice: The rain garden would move more water across the ground.

SubTopics: Present information that illustrates how a product can be created using basic processes in manufacturing systems, including forming, separating, conditioning, assembling, finishing quality control, and safety. Compare the advantages and disadvantages of human vs. computer control of these processes.
Content: :ibox:𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗤𝗨𝗘𝗦𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡 𝗛𝗔𝗦 𝗧𝗪𝗢 𝗣𝗔𝗥𝗧𝗦.

An artist made a model airplane out of solid wood. The artist began by making the body of the airplane, the wings, and other parts. Then the artist put the parts together to make the finished product.
Which of the following best describes a separation process the artist used to create the desired shape for the body of the airplane?

A.Choice: removing pieces from a block of wood

B.Choice: gluing the different wooden parts together

C.Choice: using heat to change the properties of the wood

D.Choice: sorting the different wooden parts into categories

Content: Which of the following is a finishing process?

A.Choice: placing the airplane in a display

B.Choice: painting the body of the airplane

C.Choice: making sure the airplane is to scale

D.Choice: attaching the airplane's wings to the body

SubTopics: Conduct an investigation to determine the relationships among the energy transferred, how well the type of matter retains or radiates heat, the mass, and the change in the average kinetic energy of the particles as measured by the temperature of the sample.
Content: The diagrams represent the movement of particles in two samples of the same gas. The samples are in identical, closed, glass containers. The length of an arrow represents the speed of a gas particle.
problems/MA19G8S/media/9a.jpg
Which of the following 𝗠𝗨𝗦𝗧 be different between the two samples?

SubTopics: Use a particulate model of matter to explain that density is the amount of matter (mass) in a given volume. Apply proportional reasoning to describe, calculate, and compare relative densities of different materials.
Content: A student measured three objects made of different materials. The table shows each object's mass and volume.
problems/MA19G8S/media/10a.jpg
Which of the following lists the materials in order from least dense to most dense?
The model shows Earth at two different positions during its orbit around the Sun.
problems/MA19G8S/media/11a.jpg
Which of the following explains why seasons change in Massachusetts as Earth travels around the Sun?

A.Choice: Earth's tilted axis causes uneven heating of Earth's surface by the Sun.

B.Choice: Earth's tilted axis causes the Sun to appear larger in the sky from Earth.

C.Choice: Earth's orbital distance causes uneven heating of Earth's surface by the Sun.

D.Choice: Earth's orbital distance causes the distance between Earth and the Sun to change.

SubTopics: Provide evidence that the change in an object's speed depends on the sum of the forces on the object (the net force) and the mass of the object.
Content: Four objects labeled W, X, Y, and Z have different forces applied to them. All of the horizontal forces acting on each object are shown in the diagrams.
problems/MA19G8S/media/12a.jpg
problems/MA19G8S/media/12b.jpg
problems/MA19G8S/media/12c.jpg
problems/MA19G8S/media/12d.jpg
Which table correctly classifies the four objects according to whether the speeds of the objects are changing?

SubTopics: Analyze data to provide evidence that disruptions (natural or human-made) to any physical or biological component of an ecosystem can lead to shifts in all its populations.
Content: Polar bears live in the Northern Hemisphere and need a large amount of Arctic ice to hunt. Which of the following is 𝗠𝗢𝗦𝗧 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘𝗟𝗬 to occur if the amount of Arctic ice in polar regions decreases significantly over a short period of time?

C.Choice: Polar bears will develop a larger body size.

D.Choice: Polar bears will adapt to water environments.

SubTopics: Develop a model to explain how the energy of the Sun and Earth's gravity drive the cycling of water, including changes of state, as it moves through multiple pathways in Earth's hydrosphere.
Content: The model shows water cycling through Earth's systems. The water cycle is affected by energy from the Sun and by the force of gravity.
problems/MA19G8S/media/14a.jpg
Which of the following best shows the ways that energy from the Sun and the force of gravity affect the cycling of water?

SubTopics: Develop a model to describe the relationship between the relative positions of objects interacting at a distance and their relative potential energy in the system.
Content: Several objects are located on a set of shelves in a classroom. The mass of each object is given in the table, and the diagram shows the location of each object on the set of shelves.
problems/MA19G8S/media/15a.jpg
problems/MA19G8S/media/15b.jpg
Which object has the largest potential energy relative to the floor?

SubTopics: Synthesize and communicate information about artificial selection, or the ways in which humans have changed the inheritance of desired traits in organisms.
Content: :ibox:𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗤𝗨𝗘𝗦𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡 𝗛𝗔𝗦 𝗧𝗪𝗢 𝗣𝗔𝗥𝗧𝗦.
Many traits of horses, such as coat color, are artificially selected when horses are bred.
Describe one advantage of selecting traits artificially in horses.
Describe one disadvantage of selecting traits artificially in horses.

SubTopics: Describe how relationships among and between organisms in an ecosystem can be competitive, predatory, parasitic, and mutually beneficial and that these interactions are found across multiple ecosystems.
Content: Hawks and owls are both birds of prey and often live in the same areas. Which of the following factors 𝗠𝗢𝗦𝗧 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘𝗟𝗬 limits competition for prey between hawks and owls living in the same area?

A.Choice: Hawks and owls have different predators.

B.Choice: Hawks have speckled eggs and owls have white eggs.

C.Choice: Hawks and owls are camouflaged by different feather colors.

D.Choice: Hawks are active during the day and owls are active during the night.

SubTopics: Develop and use a model to describe how parts of cells contribute to the cellular functions of obtaining food, water, and other nutrients from its environment, disposing of wastes, and providing energy for cellular processes.
Content: Some parts of a plant cell are labeled in the diagram shown.
problems/MA19G8S/media/18a.jpg
Which part of the plant cell is responsible for producing sugars?

SubTopics: Use a model to explain how thermal energy is transferred out of hotter regions or objects and into colder ones by convection, conduction, and radiation.
Content: Which of the following is the 𝗕𝗘𝗦𝗧 example of heat being transferred by conduction?

A.Choice: ocean currents moving warm water to cold water

B.Choice: mountain boulders warming up in bright sunlight

C.Choice: rocks buried in sand absorbing heat from surrounding sand

D.Choice: air masses moving from high-pressure to low-pressure regions

SubTopics: Interpret basic weather data to identify patterns in air mass interactions and the relationship of those patterns to local weather.
Content: Which of the following statements 𝗕𝗘𝗦𝗧 explains why air on Earth circulates between the equator and the poles?

A.Choice: The atmosphere is higher near the equator than at the poles.

B.Choice: The atmosphere is more dense near the equator than at the poles.

C.Choice: Earth's gravitational pull is weaker near the equator than at the poles.

D.Choice: Earth's surface temperature is greater near the equator than at the poles.
